<dl id="n56197f"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n56" href="#n56197f">N56 (VI.B.41)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n56all.htm#n56197f"> 197(f)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> layamon <font color="green">[??]</font> <small>Blue</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n56197f"><li>FW 359.17 </li><li><a href="../../flex/mf/lexmf.htm#n56197f">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/mf/l39mf.htm#n56197f">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n56197f">MS BL 47480-218v</ms> </li><li>JJA 55:420 <a name="mfd5y" href="../../ff/fdra/mda.htm#mfd5y">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/mf/mfd5.htm#n56197f">Draft: II.3&sect;6.5</a>+</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">The paramount chief of early Britain <font color="green">[King Arthur]</font>, whose prowess and conquests form the prime epic theme of Geoffrey and of <mark>Layamon</mark>, appears as the king of no known realm, numbering among his retainers heroic figures drawn from the uttermost limits of the mythical world. Exalted, as a world conqueror, to a level with Alexander and Charlemagne, he becomes, like them, largely lost to sight among the crowd of fabulous characters called up around him by the professional romancers. <small> W. Lewis Jones, <a name="WJKA5" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#WJKA5"><cite title="source">King Arthur in History and Legend</cite></a> (1914) 95</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
